	<article class="post-155014 post type-post status-publish hentry category-fixes tag-colombia tag-data-mining-and-database-marketing tag-drug-cartels des-data-mining-and-database-marketing des-drug-cartels geo-colombia" id="post-155014">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/fixes/?module=BlogCategory&version=Blog Post&action=Click&contentCollection=Opinion&pgtype=Blogs&region=Header">Fixes</a></span>
		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Colombia&#8217;s Data-Driven Fight Against Crime</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Tina Rosenberg			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-11-21T01:30:28+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">November 20, 2014 8:30 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">November 20, 2014 8:30 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div class="inlineModule"><div class="entry"><div class="thumb"><img alt="Fixes" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/opinionator/pogs/fixes45.gif" width="50" height="50"></div><p class="summary"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/fixes/">Fixes</a> looks at solutions to social problems and why they work.

</p></div></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One Monday in 1988, El Mundo newspaper of MedellÃ­n, Colombia, reported, as it did every Monday, on the violent deaths in the city of two million people over the weekend. An article giving an hour-by-hour description of the deaths from Saturday night to Sunday night was remarkable for, among other things, the journalist&#8217;s skill in finding different ways to report a murder. âSomeone took the life of LuÃ­s Alberto LÃ³pez at knife point &#8230; LuÃ­s Alberto PatiÃ±o ceased to exist with a bullet in his head &#8230; Mario Restrepo turned up dead &#8230; An unidentified person killed NÃ©stor Alvarez with three shots.â In reporting 27 different murders, the author repeated his phrasing only once.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Colombia has always been a violent country, but after the 1948 assassination of Jorge EliÃ©cer GaitÃ¡n, a politician who threatened to break the oligarchy&#8217;s stranglehold, hundreds of thousands of people were killed over the next five years. The killings were due to scorched-earth battles between the two major political parties â both parties of the upper classes whose major difference was their names.Â Violence acquired capital letters and became known as La Violencia.<br />
<span id="more-155014"></span></p>
<div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/21/opinion/21fixes-colombia/21fixes-colombia-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/21/opinion/21fixes-colombia/21fixes-colombia-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/11/21/opinion/21fixes-colombia/21fixes-colombia-blog480.jpg" id="100000003247316" width="480" height="324" alt="Colombian policemen outside a disco bar in Cali, Colombia."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="324"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Colombian policemen outside a disco bar in Cali, Colombia.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Luis Robayo/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Political violence begat other kinds of violence. The killings were worst in the countryside and millions fled to the cities, which became vast settlements of the unmoored, crowds without community â a breeding ground for crime. The judicial system and the police broke down completely during La Violencia. While most of the violence stopped after a military coup and then a pact between the two parties, the government never recovered its legitimacy nor those institutions their strength.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The dark ages returned with the rise of cocaine in the late 1970s. By the late 1980s and early 1990, the leading cause of death in several of Colombia&#8217;s major cities was homicide. The most deadly and infamous was MedellÃ­n, but this was also true in Cali.</p>
<div class="w190 right module">
<div class="entry">
<blockquote>Cali&#8217;s mayor didn&#8217;t lower homicide rates with force, he measured and mapped. </p></blockquote>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In 1983, there were 23 homicides per 100,000 people in Cali. Ten years later the rate had reached 120, and some counts put it slightly higher. That&#8217;s more than twice as high as the homicide rate ever reached in Detroit, the most dangerous city in any developed country, which peaked in 1993 at 57.6.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But crime in Cali changed after Rodrigo Guerrero became mayor.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What Guerrero did to make Cali safer was remarkable because it worked, and because of the novelty of his strategy. Before becoming mayor, Guerrero was not a politician, but a Harvard-trained epidemiologist who was president of the Universidad del Valle in Cali. He set out to prevent murder the way a doctor prevents disease. What public health workers are doing now to stop the spread of Ebola, Guerrero did in Cali to stop the spread of violence.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Although his ideas have now been used in dozens of cities throughout Latin America, they are worth revisiting because they are not employed in the places that need them most. The most violent places in Latin America are Honduras, El Salvador and Guatemala â indeed, they are among the most violent countries in the world not at war. The wave of youth migration to the United States is from these countries, and the refugees are largely fleeing violence.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One small municipality in El Salvador, Santa Tecla, has employed Cali&#8217;s strategies since about 10 years ago, and the homicide rate has dropped there. But Santa Tecla is an anomaly. Most of the region&#8217;s cities have not tried to do what Guerrero did â and they are failing to protect their citizens.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âHe was one of the pioneers,â said Mayra Buvinic, who in the 1990s was the head of the social development division and chief adviser on violence to the Inter-American Development Bank. âWith his medical background, he used an epidemiological approach to really track down and define the problem, collect reliable data and develop interventions based on data.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It was remarkable to even focus on prevention at all. âThat was not the tradition in Latin America,â said Buvinic. âUntil then, if people dealt with violence it was punitive. This was a smarter approach.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mayors in Colombia are permitted just one term at a time. After leaving office Guerrero spread his methods around Latin America and other parts of the world. In September, he became the first winner of the Roux Prize â an award of $100,000 given by the Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation for using evidence to improve public health.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When Guerrero became mayor in 1992, the conventional wisdom was that the vast bulk of Cali&#8217;s murders stemmed from disputes over cocaine trafficking â at the time, the Cali Cartel was overtaking the MedellÃ­n Cartel in control of the cocaine trade.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Guerrero didn&#8217;t assume, he measured. The police, courts and every other institution that counted murders all came up with different figures. Guerrero had weekly meetings with these groups and academic researchers to find more accurate figures. Then they mapped homicides by time and neighborhood.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">That took about a year â and his term was only two and a half years â but he found something important: deaths were concentrated on weekends, especially payday weekends. (On his first New Year&#8217;s Eve as mayor, there were 22 homicides in one night.) The same was true in MedellÃ­n, which was why El Mundo&#8217;s crime reporters needed dozens of ways to describe violent death, as the Eskimo people are said to have for snow.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThings that happen on the weekend in our country are often associated with alcohol,â Guerrero said. So Cali started to look at alcohol in the blood of victims (few perpetrators were caught) â and found a large percentage of victims had very high levels. âMy initial hypothesis was that this was drug trafficking,â he said. âBut the traffickers were not going to wait for weekends to resolve their conflicts â and get their victims drunk.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The astronomical murder rate <em>was</em> related to the cocaine trade, Guerrero concluded â but only indirectly. Cocaine created social disruption and intensified an already-violent culture. âDrug trafficking was like H.I.V.,â Guerrero said. âIt interferes with the defense mechanisms â in this case police and justice.â Those institutions were corrupted and degraded to the point where practically no one paid a penalty for murder â a suspect was identified in only 3 percent of homicides and convicted in a small percentage of those.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Guerrero banned the sale of alcohol after 1 a.m. on weeknights and 2 a.m. on Fridays and Saturdays. (That 2 a.m. is considered early closing says a lot about the problem.) As he expected, bar owners â and bar patrons â objected. Guerrero asked bars to try it for three months, but success was obvious nearly <a href="//www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3156368/">instantly</a>. The effects were big enough to overcome the objections.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The other decree banned the carrying of guns â enforced by checkpoints and pat-downs â on payday weekends and holidays. The army, which held a monopoly on the manufacture and sale of guns, fought the law. But again, success was persuasive. Researchers compared gun ban days to similar days with no ban in Cali and in BogotÃ¡, which replicated the program. They found that neighborhoods with the ban saw <a href="//jama.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=192444">14 percent fewer</a> homicides in Cali and 13 percent fewer in BogotÃ¡ than neighborhoods without restrictions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Together, those two decrees cut the homicide rate where they were instituted by 35 percent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There was more: Since the data showed that a large majority of offenders were under 24, Guerrero instituted a <a href="//webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:YF6Y3Zsz5L0J:https://www.longwoods.com/product/download/code/17590+&amp;cd=6&amp;hl=en&amp;ct=clnk&amp;gl=us&amp;client=safari">curfew</a> for young people in high crime neighborhoods between 11 p.m. and 5 a.m. on weekends.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Cali also tried to improve its police operations. The mayor ran a weekly meeting of the heads of all departments connected with law enforcement. Together, they analyzed the violence statistics for the previous week and adjusted plans accordingly â an early version of CompStat, New York Cityâs data and accountability system that was so effective in cutting crime in the 1990s. The national government established specially trained and equipped brigades to investigate crimes in Cali, and the rate of identifying perpetrators went from 3 percent to 18 percent.</p>
<div class="w190 right module">
<div class="entry">
<h6 class="kicker">Related</h6>
<h5><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/fixes">More From Fixes</a></h5>
<p class="summary">Read previous contributions to this series.</p>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The city set up programs to help police officers finish high school â only half of the force had done so. It built attractive houses for officers, in the hope (perhaps futile) that they would become more resistant to the traffickers&#8217; bribes. In addition, the city convened various city organizations â labor, business, church and others â to design programs to reduce urban violence. At the committee&#8217;s suggestion, Cali created a city agency called Desepaz, an acronym for development, security and peace. Desepaz tried to create civic connections by bringing government closer to the people. It established offices in the most dangerous neighborhoods that offered legal aid, mediation, and lawyers and social workers expert in family violence. Police departments began meeting with residents to hear their concerns.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The homicide rate declined. From its peak of 120 in 1994, it declined to 80 in 1997. Homicides also dropped in BogotÃ¡ and MedellÃ­n, which adopted Cali&#8217;s program.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Was Guerrero&#8217;s program responsible for the drop? It&#8217;s hard to separate the effects of the program from outside factors, such as the economy, Colombia&#8217;s guerrilla wars and the drug trade (most of the heads of the Cali Cartel were captured in 1995, which could cut either way on homicide). But the reduction in homicide in these three cities was much greater than in the rest of the country.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It&#8217;s difficult to say which parts were responsible. There is strong evidence that the gun and alcohol restrictions worked, but the fact that the overall rate in Cali didn&#8217;t start to drop until 1994 indicates that other pieces of the program â which were slower to implement and didn&#8217;t yield immediate results â mattered as well.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Guerrero went on to spread his ideas. Working with the Pan-American Health Organization and the Inter-American Development Bank, he took his epidemiological methods to 18 other countries.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe approach was very low-cost and pragmatic,â said Joan Serra Hoffman, a senior specialist in crime and violence prevention in Latin America and the Caribbean at the World Bank. âYou could see it was conceived by someone who was an academic and a policy maker. It can be fully operational for between $50,000 and $80,000.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The record of other cities was mixed, which was to be expected; local implementation is all. Buvinic said the best results came in cities with the highest rates of violence â the low-hanging fruit. Guerrero believes the key was having leaders willing to let the evidence guide their decisions. âIt&#8217;s much easier to let politics tell you how to use the information you collect,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Perhaps the showcase of Guerrero&#8217;s ideas is not Cali, but BogotÃ¡, which never wavered in its implementation of the program. The city&#8217;s homicide rate, which was more than 80 per 100,000 in 1993, is 16.7 per 100,000 today.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The gains did not hold in Cali, however. Mayors after Guerrero dismantled almost all the program (two left office early due to accusations of corruption or ties to traffickers). The murder rate went back up again.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But Guerrero is once again mayor of Cali, and once again, the homicide rate is dropping. This year it is on track to drop by more than 30 percent, which would put it at under 60 per 100,000.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe violence today is completely different than it was during the first term,â said Felipe Montoya, who runs Desepaz. âNow it&#8217;s organized crime.â But Guerrero&#8217;s strategy still works because it&#8217;s not a policy, it&#8217;s a process: The important piece is collecting and using data to design the approach.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Cali still closes the bars early (sort of â at 3 a.m.) on dangerous nights, and has brought back restrictions on guns and the curfews in affected neighborhoods. The city still works extensively in those neighborhoods, especially with young men â âwe&#8217;ve learned we have to stay a long time,â said Guerrero. But he said that this time the key is that Cali has gotten a lot of help from the national government: surveillance cameras, more police officers, more equipment. âTo date we&#8217;ve neutralized 86 different criminal gangs â capturing them with sufficient proof for conviction. And where we&#8217;ve neutralized the gangs, the problems disappear.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Join <a href="//www.facebook.com/home.php?#!/pages/Social-Change-New-York-Times/147881585260868">Fixes on Facebook</a> and follow updates on <a href="https://www.twitter.com/nytimesfixes">twitter.com/nytimesfixes</a>. To receive e-mail alerts for Fixes columns, sign up <a href="//eepurl.com/ABIxL" target="_blank">here.</a></em></p>
<div class="w75 left"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2010/10/18/opinion/tinaimg/tinaimg-thumbStandard-v2.jpg" alt="Tina Rosenberg" /></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Tina Rosenberg won a Pulitzer Prize for her book &#8220;<a href="//www.randomhouse.com/catalog/display.pperl?isbn=9780679744993">The Haunted Land: Facing Europeâs Ghosts After Communism</a>.&#8221; She is a former editorial writer for The Times and the author, most recently, of &#8220;<a href="//books.wwnorton.com/books/Join-the-Club/">Join the Club: How Peer Pressure Can Transform the World</a>&#8221; and the World War II spy story e-book &#8220;D for Deception.&#8221; </em></p>
	</div>
